commentBody:
@Steve L 

I went longer on Friday than I did today, but I could have never solved it had it not occurred to me that Lincoln was also a President in the 60s.

I wish he were President today.  Even if he has been dead the last 160 years.

@Puzzled 

I didn't know the mixed drink, Irish actor, or Oscar winner either (although I did see the movie... just didn't know it won) but got them all from the crossing entries without having to look them up. Banana seat was a fun one!

This one took me the same amount of time as Friday's, but it felt easier somehow.

@Jeb Jones 

On xwordstats.com, Friday's median time was 18:13.  Today's currently is 16:15.  Of course, different people have different experiences, but I think on the whole, this one was easier for more people.  

(My Friday time was almost double today's time and above the median Friday time, which is extremely unusual; today's time was significantly below the Saturday median. )

@Steve L 
I found both days challenging, but my Fri time was over 10 min longer than my Sat time (and over my average) while my Sat time was about 12 min under my Sat average. 

Statistically it seems the Sat crossword was easier for most people.

@Lpr 

I like a lot of the discussions that go on in other parts of the comments section! I just thought it might be nice to have a specific thread that is only for a nice little chat. Some days, I just want a spot to go that is away from the complaints or the commentary. It's not always clear where that is. I thought others may like that, too.

Kindness and questions probably sounds like a harsher about the other sections than it should. I think I'll just call it "Nice Little Chat" thread moving forward.

@Peter

It must have been fun to see those clues! 

(Alas, I have personal experience with only BANDTSHIRTS and SONICARE. 😂)

@Jamie 

Perhaps of the decade...but it's not the first time that ABE has been the answer to a clue about a Prez from the '60s.  But both of the other times this happened were in the last decade, in 2013, to be exact.

So don't expect to see it on Lewis's list on Monday.

@Jamie 

Yes.  I had LBJ for sooooo long.

And I was pondering what the heck jCYCLING and LIR was (I know I should have the "L" lower case, but it looks funny that way.)

@Steve L 

PS  Now we know it doesn't have to be the 1960s.

I should also mention that it also doesn't have to be an American president.  On 7/8/22, [With 45-Down, pre-marriage name of a 1940s-'50s first lady] solved to EVA.  (45D was DUARTE, the maiden name of Ms. Peron.)

@Steve L 

The thought that it might be a foreign president crossed my mind, but it scared me so much I repressed it.

Coming up with a non-US president from as long ago as any of the 60s, as a nickname or initials? Yikes!

@Jon 

I hope you reported this! 

Sounds like fowl play to me!

@HeathieJ 

I didn't have a lot to say about that one either, as I recall.  

I did love the Seinfeld reference, though.  We need a Seinfeld themed puzzle, with greatest hits that David and Seinfeld contributed to the language.

@Francis 

That would be amazing!! 

I'll add that idea to my Penske file and sit around looking annoyed all the time so you know I'm really working hard on it!

@Man and 2 dogs 

You might be onto something there.

BTW, I agree and know you're correct because that was me about 15 years ago, when comment boards first started appearing.  Some people don't want to acknowlege that I might have learned something in those 15 years that they haven't yet internalized.

@Danielle 

SHARDs! of eggshell, that is.

--- Dragonriders of Pern

@Shrike I came here for this. 
Finally I think I spotted a genuine, indisputable cluing error. 
(Looking forward to the disputes.)

@Shrike 

I'm just pointing out how crossword cluing works.  I don't have ESP, so I have no idea how that clue got there.  I do know that the constructor writes a clue, and then the editor may change the clue, and I also know that the NYT crossword has some very cagey editors.

Feel free to believe what you wish about the exegesis of this clue; I don't think it's up to us to make guesses about that of which we cannot know with certainty.

@Steve L 

Mmmm, exegesis.
How often has that been in the puzzle?

@Lex
I started with IKE, then thought it must be JFK.....
Finally cleared it all out and got the A and E from crossings.  That made it oh-so-obvious.

@Andrzej 

To "man" something tends to imply one is working there. 

Note the weasel words before you jump all over me, though.

@Andrzej 

Well, you may have a point there.

Hope I didn't mansplain earlier.

@Andrzej 
Trying - unsuccessfully - to understand the „sensible chuckle“. I looked up the meme but am not familiar with science fiction nor reddit. Is „sensible“ used to express „making sense“, or is it more like the German meaning „sensitive/feely“? It seems that the expression hints at multifarious meanings…
Glad your dog is better!

@CCNY 

We pronounce it the Spanish way - when we were planning on getting a lab, the breeder we considered first had a lab from Mexico as the sire, so we picked a Latin-sounding name (also, I love dog names with an R which I can roll as I call out 😀). In the end Jorge's father was Finnish, but we did stuck with the name we had picked originally.

@Hobby Gardener

There is nothing deeper to the meme - the thing is simply the way the guy laughs 🤪. It is a laugh but tinny and... I dunno... Chaste? Thus, sensible as in: an upper-class matron would not deem it inappropriate at dinner 😆

@Andrzej 

Hooray for Jorge!
And you paint a delightful word picture, with Jorge's nose and paw in the sunlight.

@Andrzej 

Hooray for Jorge!!  ☺️

WHATAGOODBOY!

@Andrzej 
The slipper tale with no slip-up is delightful.

When I was a kid we had a ferocious looking bulldog (part English Bull, and part some other bulldogs), who was funny and playful and absolutely to be trusted never to hurt anyone.  His only really exasperating trait was that he would help whichever kid was winning a wrestling match by shoving his nose in the ear of the kid who was losing, and starting to snuffle and nibble on the earlobe.  No choice but to give up immediately.

@Ruby
Many thought the same thing about Mr McCarty's puzzle of December 18, 2022.

Maybe his grid generating technique just follows a certain pattern.  The last one was certainly much more creepy.

@Steve L 

I didn't think you can dismiss this so easily. This is not a random, complex pattern, so it's not a pareidollic phenomenon.  It's simple and repetitive, and, due to the nature of crossword construction and the nature of the shape, some grids end up (not purposely, I'm sure) looking a little swastika-like.  This grid, not so much, in my interpretation. 

I'm all for ignoring it. Can't let perceived shapes get in the way of crossword construction.

@Ruby 
If you squint, maybe. 
On second thought, no.

@Andrzej 

I won't use them but I did rack up a ton of hints.    

This one demonstrates the key role of the puzzle title.

@Vaer 

I just enter word after word mindlessly, not understanding the theme, at all. I just see what sticks. Most words feed the hint pool.

I don't understand brute forcing a crossword though. Would that just be an alphabet run for that last square one knows not how to deal with otherwise?

@LBG 

So Perplexity is an AI-powered search engine?
I have gotten so many wrong answers from Google's AI that I would be very leery of Perplexity.

@JohnWM 

It took me a few crosses before I got PEARS. (At first pass, vases fit...) If only I had looked up: I have not one but two paintings of pears hanging in my line of sight! 

Great-aunt Patty, who by family lore was pear-shaped, painted pears. They look luscious!

@Lpr 
I should then count myself lucky, I suppose.  I needed twenty two cheats.  I definitely felt kicked in the keister.

Yes, stay safe, everyone.

@Bill 

I've done all three, some of them quite a bit 😁

And, for small bands just starting out, or having a more niche appeal, the merch is how they stay in business, so buy away!

@Grant 

During most of my concert-going days, I was too poor or too parsimonious to buy the overpriced BAND T-SHIRTS. 

A few years ago, I went to a memorial service for a coworker’s husband. He was a big music fan, so attendees were encouraged to wear their favorite band T-shirt to the service. By that time, I’d acquired a shirt from a tour by the Magnetic Fields.

@Eric Hougland 

I love that idea! And I really dig the Magnetic Fields. I believe they're on tour-!

I'm so glad I sprang for BAND T-SHIRTS in my (financially?) misspent youth, both at shows and occasionally in shops like Newbury Comics. I took good enough care of them that I still own a number of them! Glad especially since many of these bands have been coming back around, and I can for once brag about being old by wearing my old merch to the shows! Hahaha.

@G 

I think the Magnetic Fields are still doing their “69 Love Songs” anniversary tour (half the album one night, the other half the next night). 

I was sorry that they brought the show to Austin in September, about a month after we moved here. I’d have enjoyed seeing that.

@Jennifer 
That’s a great idea!
My monthly pub quiz team brings different gimmes together; DH is sport and science, Julie, natural world and geography, Rob brings all things tech and I stick with the Arts and Lit. We’re all ok on music. Strangely we hardly ever win 😄

@Marshall Walthew 

This is (one of the reasons) why I come to the comments -- fun facts I don't know I'd learn otherwise! 

I love a dark & stormy, and have been known to use it as a cocktail barometer of sorts... Goslings does make for an exceptional one. Cheers!

@Jairus 

Because people want to talk about the answers? How else do you expect people to discuss the puzzle? Why would you come to a forum discussion of a puzzle you haven't finished yet?

I am so confused.

@Jairus 

I belong to a Facebook group about the NYT crossword puzzle. The official policy is “no spoilers,” which results in people having little of interest to say about the puzzle. 

It finally got to the point where the administrator of the group started posting about puzzles with a “Spoiler Alert” heading.

@Steve L Orr last played over 4 decades ago. He may be relevant to Boomers, but he’s a footnote that lives on mostly bc of crosswords today.

Mel Ott matters even less today, since his last appearance was in *1948*.

IOW, they’re both really just xword answers now. I’m 55 and had never heard of either before I started doing this puzzle.

@Kate 
Well, I suspect you would know that making a charming post like that might spark a little interest in this crowd. Behold the 1980 Schwinn Lil’ Chik-Pretty in Pink. Some nice pictures, and if still available could be yours again for a few hundred bucks. Maybe a grand-daughter needs a bike?

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/2ca7v8eh" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/2ca7v8eh</a>

@Kate 

Ohhhhh. Right back to grade school with all the mental images (and now actual ones, thanks @Hardroch) provided in this forum today! 

My current bicycle is a practical dark gray, but it does sport a lime-green basket. Usually I don't take it out much, but spring is around the corner and maybe this year's the year!

@Lady Morgan Kelly Diana 

Fridays and Saturdays are traditionally themeless.

At least we weren't picking out the middle ORES from Oreos.

@Barry Ancona

It even made it to Indiana... almost 15 years ago.

<a href="https://www.in.gov/idem/recycle/indiana-e-cycle" target="_blank">https://www.in.gov/idem/recycle/indiana-e-cycle</a>/

@Hope Levav Thanks for sharing about your child. Certainly, I hope you’re all doing well.

I have a rare disease myself: “autosomal dominant tubulointerstitial kidney disease,” or ADTKD. (My public service announcement to all: If you run across someone with an unknown kidney disease, have them undergo a genetic test for ADTKD; learn more about the ailment at www.rarekidney.org).

Anyway: I finished in a zippy 10:25. 🙂

@Mean Old Lady 

I admit I was puzzled by your earlier comment about how Wesley must be much younger than you... I thought, I know she goes by mean - old - lady, but she can't be that old that she was around in the 1860s! ☺️

It was a pretty diabolical clue! After trying a couple options, I just left it blank and cracked up when I got the aha on the A in ABE on 23 across....

@G 

Thanks for the suggestions!  I'll definitely check them out.

Although, like you, I'm afraid of what he might be able to do to my psyche.

@JohnWM 

Nice one.   Title perhaps?:

“A Good Solve Spoiled”.
